      "settings": {
        "label": "The Science",
        "headline": "Why Your Skin Loses Its Youthful Firmness",
        "body": "<p>From our mid-20s, our skin's foundational structure begins a slow, inevitable decline. The primary culprit is a gradual loss of collagen, the protein that provides skin with its strength and firmness. This depletion occurs at a rate of approximately <strong>1% per year after the age of 25</strong>, leading to the eventual formation of fine lines and wrinkles. This process is accelerated by a lifetime of sun exposure, a key factor in what scientists call \"photoageing.\"</p><p>Simultaneously, our cells' natural repair mechanisms become less efficient. Cellular senescence, a state where cells lose their ability to divide and function, begins to accumulate. These \"zombie cells\" release inflammatory signals that degrade the surrounding healthy tissue, further accelerating the ageing process.</p><p>Deep within our cells, our DNA is under constant assault from environmental stressors. This damage accumulates over time, impairing the cell's ability to produce energy and repair itself. <strong>One landmark Australian study of 903 people showed that daily SPF 15 use resulted in 24% less skin ageing.</strong></p>",
        "bg": "muted",
        "width": "narrow",
        "cta_text": "",
        "cta_url": "",
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/Generated_Image_March_24_2026_-_12_14PM.jpg",
        "image_position": "right"
      }
    },
